for survival but many women see their options limited to the end of an

unhealthy marriage. The selection hypothesis argues “where females

predominate, they directly influence mate choice. Moerbeek and de Vries

(979) proposed the economic hypothesis: “where women do not economically

participate in the labor market, males are then retained in marriage.

Similarly Heywood (2006) argues “the role of women in Laos remains

insignificant and the male-female imbalance means women are unable to

negotiate their relationships and control the level of housework.”

Although divorce is gaining more recognition in cultural

thinking, women who violently clash with their partners to gain custody of

their children and other payments remain stigmatized and pinned as high

maintenance, or those seeking retribution.

Another reason for persistent gender inequality is the universal

cultural rejection of contraception and family planning. Encouraging

family planning brings to surface the institutional barriers to fertility

control, which have been reinforced by archaic Lao cultural practices

and religious ideals. Jude Vagramolek (1996) found that contraception was

“viewed as an expression of bad faith towards one’s future offspring.
